This tests PRD 3 US-005 (--tool filter) and US-006 (--since). The /audit endpoint already supports ?tool= and ?success= query params (http-routes.ts lines 308-309). The CLI just didn't expose them. But the server-side filtering is already implemented, so this is testing existing server functionality that's now exposed via CLI.

Extend e2e/audit-logging.e2e.ts:

```typescript
test('audit filters by tool name', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
  const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);

  // Invoke two different tools
  await callToolExpectSuccess(mcpClient, mcpServer, 'e2e-test_echo', { message: 'a' });
  await callToolExpectSuccess(mcpClient, mcpServer, 'e2e-test_greet', { name: 'Test' });

  // Query audit filtered by tool
  const res = await fetch(`http://localhost:${mcpServer.port}/audit?tool=e2e-test_echo`, {
    headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${mcpServer.secret}` },
  });
  const entries = await res.json();
  expect(entries.length).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(1);
  for (const entry of entries) {
    expect(entry.tool).toBe('e2e-test_echo');
  }

  await page.close();
});
```

For --since: the CLI does client-side filtering, so there's no new server endpoint to test. The E2E test for --since would need to test the CLI binary itself or just verify the audit entries have timestamps (which they already do).

